definitions: existing or occurring in the period before a marriage takes place
examples: Many couples attend premarital counseling sessions together
Their premarital agreement covered financial matters clearly

definitions: happening before the usual or expected time, especially too soon
not having reached full growth or development when born or emerging
examples: His premature retirement surprised everyone at the company
The premature announcement caused confusion among investors
The premature baby needed special medical care initially
These premature conclusions lack sufficient supporting evidence

definitions: thought out or planned beforehand, especially describing deliberate criminal intent
examples: The prosecutor argued it was premeditated murder
His premeditated response showed careful preparation beforehand

definitions: holding the highest position in importance, order, or rank
happening or existing before any others of the same kind
examples: She works at the premier research institution
This is the premier destination for luxury travelers
The premier showing attracted many celebrity guests
It was the premier performance of the symphony

definitions: relating to or being the first public performance or showing
examples: The premiere event featured famous actors and directors
Premiere tickets sold out within minutes of release

definitions: existing or occurring during pregnancy but before childbirth
examples: Regular prenatal checkups help monitor the baby's development
She takes prenatal vitamins every morning without fail

definitions: completely engrossed in thought to the exclusion of other things
examples: He seemed preoccupied during the entire meeting today
She was too preoccupied to notice the time

definitions: having been paid for before receiving or using something
examples: She bought a prepaid phone card for traveling
The prepaid postage made returning items much easier

definitions: serving as preparation for something more important or advanced
examples: Students take preparatory courses before entering medical school
The preparatory work laid foundation for the project

definitions: made ready beforehand for a specific purpose or event
willing and able to deal with something that might happen
examples: The prepared meals just need reheating before serving
All prepared statements were reviewed by legal counsel
She felt prepared for any questions they might ask
The prepared students performed well on the exam

definitions: relating to or formed with a preposition in grammar
examples: The prepositional phrase modifies the main verb clearly
Students struggle with prepositional usage in foreign languages

definitions: contrary to reason or common sense; utterly absurd or ridiculous
examples: His preposterous claim that he invented the internet
The preposterous price made everyone laugh in disbelief

definitions: recorded in advance rather than broadcast or played live
examples: The prerecorded message played when nobody answered calls
They used prerecorded music for the stage performance

definitions: required as a prior condition for something else to happen
examples: Basic math is prerequisite for advanced calculus courses
Experience is prerequisite for this senior management position

definitions: having or showing knowledge of events before they take place
examples: Her prescient warnings about the market crash proved accurate
The prescient investor sold before prices dropped significantly

definitions: recommended or ordered by medical authority as a remedy
established or laid down as a rule or course of action
examples: She takes prescribed medication twice daily without fail
The prescribed treatment helped reduce his chronic pain
Students must follow prescribed procedures for lab safety
The prescribed format ensures consistency across all documents

definitions: giving rules or directions about how something should be done
examples: The prescriptive approach tells students exactly what's correct
Their prescriptive guidelines left no room for creativity

definitions: serving to preserve something, especially food, from decay or spoiling
examples: Natural preservative ingredients extend the product's shelf life
Foods without preservative chemicals spoil much more quickly

definitions: maintained in its original or existing state without decay
kept safe from harm or unchanged over time
examples: The preserved fruit lasted through the long winter
Preserved wood resists rot and insect damage effectively
These preserved traditions connect us to our ancestors
The preserved documents provide valuable historical insights today

definitions: arranged, adjusted, or set up beforehand for automatic operation
examples: The preset temperature keeps the room comfortably warm
Use preset options to save time when editing

definitions: made flat or smooth by applying weight or pressure
subjected to urgent demands or harassment
examples: She wore a freshly pressed shirt to the interview
The pressed flowers decorated the handmade greeting cards
Time pressed, they had to make a quick decision
He felt pressed to accept the offer immediately

definitions: requiring quick or immediate action or attention
examples: The pressing deadline forced them to work overtime
She had more pressing matters to attend to

definitions: inspiring respect and admiration through perceived quality or reputation
examples: He graduated from a prestigious university with honors
The prestigious award recognized her lifetime scientific achievements

definitions: based on probability or presumption rather than certainty
examples: The presumptive heir prepared to inherit the estate
Presumptive evidence suggested his involvement in the case

definitions: relating to or being a child between nine and twelve years old
examples: The preteen section offers age-appropriate books and activities
Many preteen children experience rapid physical changes then

definitions: not real or true but made to appear so
examples: His pretended interest fooled nobody at the meeting
She saw through his pretended concern pretty quickly

definitions: attempting to impress by affecting greater importance or merit than possessed
examples: His pretentious manner annoyed everyone at the party
The pretentious restaurant served tiny portions on huge plates

definitions: most frequent or common at a particular time and place
existing at a particular time and continuing to exist
examples: The prevailing winds blow from west to east here
Prevailing opinion favored the new policy proposal strongly
Under prevailing conditions, the project cannot move forward
The prevailing atmosphere was one of cautious optimism

definitions: widespread in a particular area or at a particular time
examples: This disease is particularly prevalent among young children
Smartphones have become prevalent in modern society everywhere

definitions: capable of being stopped from happening through appropriate measures
examples: Most accidents are preventable with proper safety precautions
This preventable disease still affects millions worldwide unfortunately

definitions: designed to stop something undesirable from occurring or arising
examples: Regular exercise is a preventative measure against heart disease
The preventative maintenance schedule reduces equipment failure significantly

definitions: designed to stop something harmful or undesirable from happening
examples: Preventive medicine focuses on maintaining good health naturally
They took preventive action to avoid system failure

definitions: existing or occurring in the period before a war
examples: The prewar economy was much more stable overall
They restored the building to its prewar condition

definitions: so precious that its value cannot be determined in money
causing great amusement because of absurdity or surprise
examples: The museum houses priceless artifacts from ancient civilizations
Her priceless advice helped me through difficult times
His priceless expression when surprised made everyone laugh
The comedian's priceless timing delivered perfect punchlines consistently

definitions: covered with prickles or thorns that can pierce skin
quick to take offense or difficult to deal with
examples: The prickly cactus requires careful handling when repotting
Prickly bushes protect the garden from unwanted intruders
She becomes prickly when questioned about personal matters
His prickly personality made teamwork challenging at times

definitions: relating to or befitting a priest or the priesthood
examples: He wore traditional priestly robes during the ceremony
Her priestly duties included counseling troubled congregation members

definitions: stiffly formal and respectable in manner or appearance
examples: Her prim appearance matched her conservative teaching style
The prim hostess disapproved of their casual attire

definitions: relating to an early stage in development; fundamental and instinctive
examples: Fear triggers our primal instinct for self-preservation naturally
The primal forces of nature shaped the landscape

definitions: made ready for use or action through preparation
examples: The athletes were primed for peak performance today
The primed surface accepts paint much more evenly

definitions: belonging to the first or earliest age or ages
examples: The primeval forest remained untouched by human development
Primeval instincts still influence our modern behavior patterns

definitions: relating to an early stage of human or cultural development
not developed or derived from anything else; basic and fundamental
examples: Primitive tools were made from stone and wood
These primitive societies had complex social structures nonetheless
The cabin had only primitive facilities for cooking
His primitive understanding of physics limited his progress

definitions: existing at or from the beginning of time; fundamental and ancient
examples: Life emerged from the primordial soup billions ago
These primordial emotions connect all human beings together

definitions: suitable for or characteristic of a prince in dignity
magnificent or generous in amount, especially regarding money
examples: He maintained a princely bearing despite humble origins
The princely manor impressed all who visited there
She received a princely sum for her artwork
His princely gift to charity made headlines nationally

definitions: acting in accordance with morality and showing consistent ethical standards
examples: Her principled stand against corruption earned widespread respect
The principled leader refused to compromise core values

definitions: suitable or fit to be printed or published publicly
examples: Please provide a printable version of the document
His comments were barely printable in family newspapers

definitions: showing the colors of the spectrum produced by a prism
examples: The prismatic effect created beautiful rainbow patterns everywhere
Prismatic glass breaks white light into component colors

definitions: in its original condition; unspoiled and perfectly clean
fresh and clean as if new or untouched
examples: The pristine beaches attracted tourists seeking natural beauty
She kept her car in pristine condition always
The pristine wilderness remains protected from commercial development
These pristine manuscripts survived centuries in monastery vaults

definitions: having special rights, advantages, or immunities not available to everyone
legally protected from being made public, as certain communications
examples: The privileged students attended exclusive private schools regularly
His privileged background opened many doors for him
Attorney-client conversations remain privileged under the law
This privileged information cannot be shared with outsiders

definitions: sharing in the knowledge of something secret or private
examples: Only senior staff were privy to expansion plans
She was privy to confidential information about mergers

definitions: creating or controlling situations by taking initiative rather than responding
examples: The proactive approach prevented many potential problems later
Successful managers take proactive steps to improve productivity
